<font color="#FF0000">SPECIAL CASES</font><br>
<tt>Fri Nov  7 22:02:14 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
As a Commanding Officer of a Basic Infantry Training Company, I had the occassion to work with a young Private Recruit E-1.<br>
Although he was very young, he appeared very mature. He was very physically fit and intelligent (not educated) and applied himself to every task with total effort.  His platoon sergeant and all the drill instructors viewed him with admiration and favor.<br>
At the end of his training cycle, I called him into my office and informed him (much to his surprise) that he was being given a hardship discharge.  Since his father had died, he had become the sole support for his mother and numerous siblings.  As an uneducated blue collar worker he had managed for several years of his young life to support his family without welfare support.<br>
He looked at me as though embarrassed, then hung his head. &quot;Sir, the army don't pay much,&quot; he said in a soft practical way.<br>
I spent a day or two, personally escourting this young man around the post to get him processed expediously out of the army, something a Captain seldom does.  I drove him to the bus station.  Before he boarded, I informed him in no uncertain manner that I thought he was a fine soldier..and that I had been priviledged to have been his commander.<br>
I'm glad he didn't have to go..I wonder how many young men of character, like him, went without complaint.  It amplifies my contempt for cry babies and bullshit peddlers that found bogus ways to evade the war.<br><br>
Mustang Two Four
